# simple matrix power using spectrum decomposition
matrix_power <- function(A, p) {
  eig <- eigen(A)
  V <- eig$vectors
  L <- eig$values
  V %*% diag(L ^ p) %*% t(V)
}

p <- 2; q <- 3; n <- 70
r11sqrt <- matrix_power(r11, -1/2)
r22sqrt <- matrix_power(r22, -1/2)
A <- r11sqrt %*% r12 %*% solve(r22, r21) %*% r11sqrt
B <- r22sqrt %*% r21 %*% solve(r11, r12) %*% r22sqrt
eigA <- eigen(A)
eigB <- eigen(B)
cat("Sample canonical correlations:")
## Sample canonical correlations:
sqrt(eigA$values)
## [1] 0.6879479 0.1868654
cat("First canonical pair:")
## First canonical pair:
eigA$vectors[, 1] %*% r11sqrt # U_1
##            [,1]       [,2]
## [1,] -0.7689274 -0.2720729
eigB$vectors[, 1] %*% r22sqrt # V_1
##             [,1]       [,2]       [,3]
## [1,] -0.04912716 -0.8975114 -0.1900411
# tesing
stat <- -(n-1-(p+q+1)/2) * log(prod(1 - eigA$values))
stat
## [1] 44.65657
alpha <- .05
crit <- qchisq(1-alpha, p*q)
stat > crit # reject H0 if this is true
## [1] TRUE
stat1 <- -(n-1-(p+q+1)/2) * log(1 - eigA$values[2])
stat1 > crit # reject H0^(1) if this is true
## [1] FALSE

a), b) Sample canonical correlations and first canonical pairs are shown above.

In the testing, we reject \(H_0\) at the \(\alpha=.05\) level but do not reject \(H_0^{(1)}: \rho_1^* \ne 0, \rho_2^* = 0\).

  1. After some direct calculations, we obtain the table as follows | \(X^{(1)}\) | \(\hat U_1\) | \(\hat V_1\) | \(X^{(2)}\) | \(\hat U_1\) | \(\hat V_1\) | | :: | :: | :: | :: | :: | :: | | \(X^{(1)}_1\) | .99 | .68 | \(X^{(2)}_1\) | .29 | .42 | | \(X^{(1)}_2\) | .89 | .61 | \(X^{2)}_2\) | .68 | .98 | | | | | \(X^{2)}_3\) | .35 | .51 |

  2. \(\hat U_1\) measures the consumption levels of households, while \(\hat V_1\) is some measure of status of households based primarily on family income (also educational level and age of head).

  3. We can see that status of families is positively correlated with their consumption levels. That is to say, households with higher income tend to consume more. Conversely, families with higher consumption levels are often wealthier.

plotqq <- function(col, title="") {
  qqp <- qqnorm(col, main = title)
  qqline(col)
  with(qqp, cor(x, y))
}
layout(matrix(1:10, nrow = 2, byrow = TRUE), respect = TRUE)
par(mar=rep.int(1,4))
nonmult.rqs <-  sapply(nonmult, plotqq)
mult.rqs <-  sapply(mult, plotqq)

nonmult_avg <- colMeans(nonmult)
mult_avg <- colMeans(mult)
S1 <- cov(nonmult)
S2 <- cov(mult)
Spool <- ((n1-1) * S1 + (n2-1) * S2) / (n1+n2-2)
d <- nonmult_avg - mult_avg
coefs <- solve(Spool, d) # coefs of discriminant function
coefs
##          V1          V2          V3          V4          V5 
##  0.02340633 -0.03446657  0.21027081 -0.08393327 -0.25345069
m <- sum(solve(Spool, d) * (nonmult_avg + mult_avg) / 2)
m # mhat
## [1] -23.23392

As shown above, we allocate x0 to \(\pi_1\) if \(.023x_1 - .034x_2 + .21x_3 - .08x_4 - .25x_5 + 23.23 \ge 0\) Otherwise, allocate it to \(\pi_2\) From this function, we know that first two variables appeart to be less important.

predicted1 <- as.matrix(nonmult) %*% coefs
conf <- matrix(nrow = 2, ncol = 2)
conf[1,1] <- sum(predicted1 >= m)
conf[1,2] <- n1 - conf[1,1]

# mult
predicted2 <- as.matrix(mult) %*% coefs
conf[2,1] <- sum(predicted2 >= m)
conf[2,2] <- n2 - conf[2,1]

# confusion matrix
conf
##      [,1] [,2]
## [1,]   66    3
## [2,]    7   22
APER <- (conf[1,2] + conf[2,1]) / (n1 + n2)
APER
## [1] 0.1020408
